This book was in all probability the Sosus, a dialogue in which Antiochus attacked the views os his old teacher Philo¹. The terms in ’ which Cicero speaks of it show that it covered exactly the same ground as the discussions which Lucullus professes to report. The Sosus was probably divided into several books, one os them containinga purely personal attack upon Philo, which Cicero passed over in writing the Acadonr'ca'. The sources of the sceptical arguments in the Academica are scarcely less clear. A work os Philo, twice mentioned, though not by any definite title⁸, supplied Cicero with the historica] justification of the New Academy which, in the first edition, he opposed to the speech os Hortensius, and in the second to that of Varro⁴. From the same work, in all probability, came the historical references placed at the outset of Cicero’s speech in the LmIIusk It is not quite so easy to trace to their origin the argu· ments by which Cicero showed the delusive nature of sense-knowledge. They were common-places of debate used by all philosophical sceptics from Pyrrho to Sextus. It is more probable that they were here bor- rowcd from Clitomachus than from any other writer⁶. The ‘four heads’ oi the sceptic argument, which Cicero in his later speech mentions in close connexion with the criticism directed in his earlier speech against the senses, are entirely in the style of Clitomachus⁷. The same book undoubtedly supplied Cicero with the more elaborate criticism on the bases of knowledge which he embodied in his second speeeh⁸. Tradition has, however, only handed down to us the titles of a few os the four hundred books which Clitomachus is said to have written, and no one os these titles suits the circumstances of the present case. Cicero next gives two extracts relating to the constructive side of Carneades' philosophy, taken from two works os Clitomachus which he names⁰.
